[[File:Observatory car suspended from Zeppelin Scientific American 1916-12-23 crop5.jpg|thumb|right|Observatory car drawing from a December 1916 ''Scientific American'' cover]] [[File:JuraySpaehGondel.jpg|thumb|right|Juray fish-shaped spy gondola while manned]] The '''Spy gondola''', '''Spy basket''', '''Observation car''' or '''sub-cloud car''' ({{lang-de|Spähgondel}} or {{lang|de|Spähkorb}}) was a byproduct of ''Peilgondel'' development (a gondola to weight an airship's radio-locating antenna). They were used almost entirely by the Germans in the [[World War I|First World War]] on their military [[airship]]s. The spy basket could be lowered from above through the cloud deck several hundred metres,<ref>Captain [[Ernst A. Lehmann]]'s book</ref> in order to inconspicuously observe the ground and to help navigate the airship.
==Development== The ''Peilgondel'' was developed by [[Paul Jaray]] to act as a heavy [[plumbbob]] for an airship's radio antenna. A free-hanging antenna wire would move and flex in the wind hindering communications; the added weight reduced this movement. Jaray then developed the ''Peilgondel'' further into a manned spy gondola.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012|reason=a) Nothing found about antenna. b) Nothing found about spy basket, Lehmann not mentioned him.}}
== Use == [[File:USS Macon spy basket 1934.jpg|thumb|right|An aeroplane photographed this spy basket in operation hanging from the American [[USS Macon (ZRS-5)|USS Macon]] in 1934-09-27.]]Spy baskets were used on, among others, [[Schütte-Lanz]] and [[Zeppelin]] airships. {{As of|1937}}, it was not always certain which airships used them: the blueprints for [[List of Zeppelins#LZ62|LZ 62]] (L 30) and [[List of Zeppelins#LZ72|LZ 72]] (L 31) included the spy basket operating plant but the German Navy was no longer installing them at that time; however a fish-shaped spy basket can be seen on photographs of the German Army [[List of Zeppelins#LZ83|LZ 83]] (tactical number LZ 113).<ref name=museum>[[#Horn|Horn, Andreas]]</ref>After the war the Americans briefly experimented with a spy basket on the {{USS|Akron|ZRS-4|6}}.<ref>DEPARTMENT OF THE NAVY -- NAVAL HISTORICAL CENTER [http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/ac-usn22/z-types/zrs5-o.htm USS Macon (ZRS-5)]</ref>
== Zeppelin spy basket development and use == Captain [[Ernst A. Lehmann]], the German airship captain, described in his book ''The Zeppelins'' how he and [[Baron Gemmingen]], [[Ferdinand von Zeppelin|Count Zeppelin]]'s nephew, had developed the device. To test the prototype he blindfolded the helmsman of the airship and allowed himself to be lowered by a winch from the bombroom in a modified cask, equipped with a telephone. Hanging some {{convert|500|ft|order=flip}} below the airship using a compass he could tell the helmsman which bearing to take and effectively drive the airship.<ref name=Lehmann>[[#Lehmann|Lehmann, The Zeppelins]]</ref> He later recounted how, while returning from the aborted raid on London in March 1916<ref name="Syon104">[[#Syon|Syon 2001 page 104]]</ref> in the [[List of Zeppelins#LZ26|Z 12]], Baron Gemmingen insisted on being the first to use it on their secondary target, Calais. The basket was equipped with a wicker chair, chart table, electric lamp, compass, telephone,<ref name="Syon104"/> and lightning conductor. With the Zeppelin sometimes within, sometimes above the clouds and unable to see the ground, Gemmingen in the hanging basket would relay orders on navigation and when and which bombs to drop. The Calais defenders could hear the engines but their searchlights and artillery fire did not reach the airship.<ref name=Lehmann/>
LZ26's basket was lowered from the airship on a specially constructed tether {{convert|1000|m|ft}} long;<ref name="Lehmann"/> other airships may have used one approximately {{convert|750|m|ft}} long.<ref name="Syon104"/> The tether was high grade steel with a brass core insulated with rubber to act as the telephone cable.<ref name="Lehmann"/>
Despite Gemmingen reporting a feeling of loneliness while being lowered and losing sight of the airship, crewmen would nevertheless volunteer for this duty because it was the one place they could smoke.<ref name="Syon104"/>
==Surviving examples== [[File:IWMzeppelinspybasket.JPG|thumb|right|A spy basket preserved at the [[Imperial War Museum]], which fell from the [[List of Zeppelins#LZ60|LZ 90]] on 2 to 3 September 1916.<ref name=iwm>{{cite web |url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30000193 |title=Zeppelin Observation Car ('Cloud Car') |work=Collection Search |author=Imperial War Museum |accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref>]] The [[Imperial War Museum]] in London exhibits a Zeppelin observation car that was found near [[Colchester]] after the Zeppelin air raid on the night of the September 2-3, 1916. It is believed to have been carried by the [[List of Zeppelins#LZ90|LZ 90]] and was being deployed unmanned when the winch accidentally ran out of control. It was found along with 1500 metres of cable. The winch was jettisoned near [[Bury St. Edmunds]].<ref name=iwm/>
==In fiction== The spy basket's use is dramatized in the 1930 film ''[[Hell's Angels (film)|Hell's Angels]]''. In the long running British comic [[Charley's War]], a ruthless German airship commander orders the jettisoning of his ship's cloud car (with the observer still in it) in order to save weight when his airship comes under attack.
